":"1225–Deceased","1236–Male":"1236–Deceased","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","1183–Male":"1183–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1238":"1238","about 1208":"about 1208","1225":"1225","1236":"1236","1214":"1214","1210":"1210","ABT 1236":"about 1236","ABT 1238":"about 1238","about 1231":"about 1231","1183":"1183","Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Flint (Clwyd),Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Clwyd, Flintshire, Wales":"Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom","Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom":"Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Iorwerth ap Griffri was born in 1210, in Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Griffri Ab Ieuaf and Mrs. Griffri ab Ieuaf. He married Margred Verch Cynwrig Fychan about 1231, in Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1210–":"1210–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1183–Male":"1183–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1238":"1238","about 1208":"umbes 1208","1225":"1225","1236":"1236","1214":"1214","1210":"1210","ABT 1236":"umbes 1236","ABT 1238":"umbes 1238","about 1231":"umbes 1231","1183":"1183","Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Flint (Clwyd),Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Clwyd, Flintshi